  }, "The Temperance movement started before the Eighteenth Amendment. Across the country many people began arguing that alcohol was morally corrupting and hurting families economically. Claiming men would drink their family's money away. This temperance movement paved the way for some women to join the Prohibition movement, which they often felt was necessary due to their personal experiences dealing with drunk husbands and fathers. Also, it was one of the few ways for women to enter politics at the time. One of the most notable groups that pushed for Prohibition was the Woman's Christian Temperance Union.")), /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("div", {
