      lineNumber: 93,
      columnNumber: 5
    }
  }, "Opposition There was opposition to Prohibition during and after the fight for it. The belief that women would vote as a block, a widespread fear during the suffrage movement, was proven wrong with the development of the Women's Organization for National Prohibition Reform. There were also many women who joined auxiliary groups to fight alongside their husbands or other male relations against the 18th Amendment. Women's Organization for National Prohibition Reform", /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("div", {
    className: "container",
    __self: this,
    __source: {
      fileName: _jsxFileName,
      lineNumber: 97,
      columnNumber: 7
    }
  }, "Time magazine cover July 18, 1932, featuring Pauline Morton Sabin, founder and head of the WONPR. The Women\u2019s Organization for National Prohibition Reform was organized on May 28th, 1929 in Chicago. Five national committees were formed, including: Investigation, Publicity, Speakers\u2019 Bureau, Legislative, and Membership. The organization was financed by voluntary contributions and not membership dues. At their peak they had over a million members. The primary founder, Pauline Morton Sabin, gathered the group following after Ella Boole proclaimed to Congress that she represented all women. The WONPR's argument against Prohibition was its ineffectiveness and how it encouraged disrespect of the law and the Constitution. Bootlegging was common, and once the Great Depression began, many were hoping simply for more jobs and the tax money that would come from legal selling of alcohol again.[15]"), /*#__PURE__*/React.createElement("div", {
